ocentric.\n- not very willing to further his education.\n- puts concern for others above everything.\n- excellent attention skills.\n\nCandidate D:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately.\n- can concentrate very well.\n- solves problems extremely well.\n- takes responsibility seriously.\n- considered moody.\n- regarded as a loner.\n\nNow we need to evaluate for long-distance pilot role. Criteria: reliability, technical competence, calm under pressure, decision-making, teamwork/communication, professional development.\n\nWe need to weigh strengths and weaknesses. Let's assess each:\n\nA: Strengths: anticipates dangerous situations (good safety), sees complex connections (systems thinking), excellent spatial vision (important for navigation), very good leadership. Weaknesses: unfriendly (teamwork), eats unhealthily (could affect health for long flights). No explicit calmness under pressure, reliability unknown. Leadership good but unfriendly may hinder crew cooperation. Health concerns.\n\nB: Strengths: keeps calm in crisis (calm under pressure), 100% reliable (reliability), good at assessing weather (technical), excellent computer skills (tech). Weaknesses: pretentious, sometimes wrong tone (communication issues), maybe interpersonal. No explicit teamwork but reliability and calmness strong.\n\nC: Strengths: makes correct decisions quickly (decision-making), puts concern for others above everything (crew care), excellent attention skills (focus). Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not willing to further education (professional development), maybe not team oriented due to egocentric but also caring. Mixed.\n\nD: Strengths: responds to unexpected events adequately (adaptability), concentrates well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously (responsibility). Weaknesses: moody, loner (teamwork), maybe interpersonal issues.\n\nNow we need to decide best candidate. Likely B seems strongest: reliability, calmness, technical weather assessment, computer skills. Communication issues (pretentious, wrong tone) could be mitigated but still a concern. However, A has leadership but unfriendly and health issues. C has good decision-making and caring but communication difficulty and egocentric. D has problem solving but moody and loner.\n\nThus B likely best overall. But we should ask other agents if they have any info on candidate B's teamwork or crew cooperation, or candidate D's interpersonal skills, to confirm. However we already asked Agent2 and they said no info. Maybe ask Agent1 about candidate C's teamwork or communication? We have some info: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, puts concern for others above everything. Could ask about any positive teamwork aspects. But we have that.\n\nWe could ask Agent1 about candidate D's moodiness impact on crew? Already known moody. Maybe ask about candidate A's reliability? Already unknown. Could ask Agent1 about candidate A's calmness? Already unknown.\n\nThus we have enough to make a vote. We should state reasoning and vote for Candidate B.\n\nNow produce public message with reasoning, referencing known attributes, weighing pros/cons, and final vote."}
